WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.600 --> 00:00:02.850
PAUL LEE: My name is Paul Lee.

00:00:02.850 --> 00:00:04.952
And I'm a product
manager here at Google.

00:00:04.952 --> 00:00:06.660
For the past several
years, my wife and I

00:00:06.660 --> 00:00:08.400
have had the pleasure
of volunteering

00:00:08.400 --> 00:00:10.150
with the International
Justice Mission.

00:00:10.150 --> 00:00:12.790
And today, I am
privileged to introduce

00:00:12.790 --> 00:00:15.230
its founder and CEO Gary Haugen.

00:00:15.230 --> 00:00:18.010
So who is Gary Haugen?

00:00:18.010 --> 00:00:19.520
I didn't fact check this.

00:00:19.520 --> 00:00:21.490
So we'll go with this.

00:00:21.490 --> 00:00:24.430
This is what the
internet says Gary is.

00:00:24.430 --> 00:00:26.940
Gary is the youngest
of six kids and hails

00:00:26.940 --> 00:00:28.441
from nearby Sacramento.

00:00:28.441 --> 00:00:29.940
During elementary
school, he decided

00:00:29.940 --> 00:00:32.398
he want to be a lawyer, inspired
by the examples of Lincoln

00:00:32.398 --> 00:00:33.770
and MLK.

00:00:33.770 --> 00:00:36.010
He played football
in high school,

00:00:36.010 --> 00:00:37.790
with the scene crew
cut he generously

00:00:37.790 --> 00:00:39.480
shares with us today.

00:00:39.480 --> 00:00:42.180
And in 1981, he departed
for the lesser school

00:00:42.180 --> 00:00:44.100
in the East Coast, Harvard.

00:00:44.100 --> 00:00:48.090
After graduating in 1985,
Gary traveled to South Africa

00:00:48.090 --> 00:00:49.690
during the apartheid
era, and worked

00:00:49.690 --> 00:00:51.720
with Michael Cassidy
and Desmond Tutu

00:00:51.720 --> 00:00:55.260
at the National Initiative
for Reconciliation.

00:00:55.260 --> 00:00:57.200
For those of you who
were born in the '80s,

00:00:57.200 --> 00:00:59.330
this was during
the apartheid era.

00:00:59.330 --> 00:01:01.870
And as an example of what
it was like in that period,

00:01:01.870 --> 00:01:05.040
in one instance Gary was
detained by security forces

00:01:05.040 --> 00:01:06.900
for attending a
multiracial church

00:01:06.900 --> 00:01:08.760
service without permission.

00:01:08.760 --> 00:01:11.520
This was a world at that time.

00:01:11.520 --> 00:01:14.126
In 1988, Gary started law school
at the University of Chicago.

00:01:14.126 --> 00:01:16.500
And during that time, he worked
for the Lawyers Committee

00:01:16.500 --> 00:01:17.330
on Human Rights.

00:01:17.330 --> 00:01:20.840
He investigated crimes like
Lupeau Massacre of 1987,

00:01:20.840 --> 00:01:23.020
which involved the
execution of 17 civilians

00:01:23.020 --> 00:01:25.570
by soldiers in
the Filipino army.

00:01:25.570 --> 00:01:27.890
After law school, Gary joined
the Department of Justice

00:01:27.890 --> 00:01:30.402
as a trial attorney in
the Civil Rights Division.

00:01:30.402 --> 00:01:32.110
Gary met his wife,
Jan, during this time.

00:01:32.110 --> 00:01:33.750
They now have four kids.

00:01:33.750 --> 00:01:36.790
And in 1994, Gary was
detailed to the UN Center

00:01:36.790 --> 00:01:40.100
for Human Rights, where he
directed the UN's investigation

00:01:40.100 --> 00:01:42.070
of the genocide in Rwanda.

00:01:42.070 --> 00:01:44.540
I actually have on my
computer, but didn't

00:01:44.540 --> 00:01:47.665
send it to Ruthie in time,
a photo, my favorite photo

00:01:47.665 --> 00:01:49.400
that I've seen in
the IJM office.

00:01:49.400 --> 00:01:53.620
It's a picture of a
giant military camouflage

00:01:53.620 --> 00:01:57.170
helicopter in the
background, Gary

00:01:57.170 --> 00:01:59.610
dressed pretty much
like he is right now,

00:01:59.610 --> 00:02:02.630
and scores of kids
running towards him.

00:02:02.630 --> 00:02:04.300
And I asked the
staff there, what

00:02:04.300 --> 00:02:05.990
is that photo,
because it's just kick

00:02:05.990 --> 00:02:09.220
butt to see this giant
military transport and all

00:02:09.220 --> 00:02:10.479
these kids and Gary.

00:02:10.479 --> 00:02:13.990
It turns out that it was
from 2006, his first trip

00:02:13.990 --> 00:02:17.920
back to Rwanda where he
visited a remote area that

00:02:17.920 --> 00:02:19.880
was part of his investigation.

00:02:19.880 --> 00:02:24.460
That time was pivotal,
and if we go back to 1994,

00:02:24.460 --> 00:02:26.770
Gary, when he worked
for the investigation,

00:02:26.770 --> 00:02:30.030
collected with his team,
testimony of physical evidence

00:02:30.030 --> 00:02:32.060
from 100 mass
graves and massacre

00:02:32.060 --> 00:02:34.050
sites across the country.

00:02:34.050 --> 00:02:36.785
Allow me to share because I
can't do this justice, the "New

00:02:36.785 --> 00:02:38.910
Yorker" subscription as
experienced from an article

00:02:38.910 --> 00:02:41.520
they wrote about this in 2009.

00:02:41.520 --> 00:02:44.320
"Gary was sickened to come
across charred piles of bodies

00:02:44.320 --> 00:02:47.547
in a church where Tutsi had
expected to find sanctuary.

00:02:47.547 --> 00:02:49.130
He took down the
testimony of a father

00:02:49.130 --> 00:02:52.620
who saw his three small children
hacked to death with machetes.

00:02:52.620 --> 00:02:54.950
At one massacre site,
Haugen rolled back

00:02:54.950 --> 00:02:57.240
the decaying body of
a woman, and found

00:02:57.240 --> 00:02:59.300
the corpse of her
child beneath her."

00:02:59.300 --> 00:03:00.950
End quote.

00:03:00.950 --> 00:03:05.050
Over the next 17 years--
sorry, let me back up.

00:03:05.050 --> 00:03:08.300
Moved by this experience,
Gary returned to the US

00:03:08.300 --> 00:03:11.050
and went into start-up
planning mode.

00:03:11.050 --> 00:03:12.570
He would build a
new organization

00:03:12.570 --> 00:03:14.780
that would not simply
plead for victims,

00:03:14.780 --> 00:03:16.840
but would actually rescue them.

00:03:16.840 --> 00:03:19.710
This organization would
focus on four key areas.

00:03:19.710 --> 00:03:23.620
Victim relief, perpetrator
accountability, aftercare

00:03:23.620 --> 00:03:25.610
and structural reform.

00:03:25.610 --> 00:03:28.930
In 1997, one year prior
to Google's own start,

00:03:28.930 --> 00:03:31.700
Gary found IJM with
one employee, desks

00:03:31.700 --> 00:03:34.390
for two interns
in an office park.

00:03:34.390 --> 00:03:37.600
Over the next 17 years, IJM
would establish operations

00:03:37.600 --> 00:03:39.500
in 10 countries
and earn the right

00:03:39.500 --> 00:03:41.640
to investigate and
prosecute crimes,

00:03:41.640 --> 00:03:43.120
working with local
law enforcement

00:03:43.120 --> 00:03:44.910
and public prosecutors.

00:03:44.910 --> 00:03:47.730
You won't see these
videos, but I've seen them.

00:03:47.730 --> 00:03:51.200
And what you'll see if you were
actually at IJM headquarters

00:03:51.200 --> 00:03:52.960
is pictures of staff
putting their lives

00:03:52.960 --> 00:03:57.060
on the line in the back of
SWAT vans, raiding brothels,

00:03:57.060 --> 00:04:00.020
chasing out the aggressors
and rescuing the victims.

00:04:00.020 --> 00:04:02.540
It's a pretty
powerful experience.

00:04:02.540 --> 00:04:05.390
The organization now
includes 600 staff,

00:04:05.390 --> 00:04:06.890
including an
investigations team led

00:04:06.890 --> 00:04:10.390
by Mark Clookie, the former
director of NCIS-- yes, he

00:04:10.390 --> 00:04:14.780
did do two cameos on a TV show--
a policy team led by Holly

00:04:14.780 --> 00:04:17.950
Burkhalter, former advocacy
director for Human Rights

00:04:17.950 --> 00:04:21.050
Watch, as well as 200 lawyers.

00:04:21.050 --> 00:04:24.610
Today IJM is a $50 million
human rights agency

00:04:24.610 --> 00:04:27.760
that, in the words of the
"Atlantic"'s Stephen Bradley,

00:04:27.760 --> 00:04:32.620
investigates and prosecutes the
worst crimes, the worst evils,

00:04:32.620 --> 00:04:34.380
around the globe.

00:04:34.380 --> 00:04:37.650
Human trafficking, sexual
exploitation, slavery,

00:04:37.650 --> 00:04:41.170
police brutality, violence
in all manifestation

00:04:41.170 --> 00:04:45.194
but principally violence
against the world's poor.

00:04:45.194 --> 00:04:47.110
Over the last years,
I've served on the board.

00:04:47.110 --> 00:04:50.130
I've worked in my career
with over 40 non-profits.

00:04:50.130 --> 00:04:51.880
And some of these
non-profits are amazing.

00:04:51.880 --> 00:04:53.332
I think they do incredible work.

00:04:53.332 --> 00:04:55.540
This is the first time I
worked with a nonprofit that

00:04:55.540 --> 00:04:59.180
has as its dashboard monitoring
loss of life and limb

00:04:59.180 --> 00:05:03.230
to staff, tracking assassination
attempts on their staff workers

00:05:03.230 --> 00:05:04.150
in the field.

00:05:04.150 --> 00:05:06.680
The work they do is
really incredible.

00:05:06.680 --> 00:05:10.870
In 2013 alone, IJM
rescued over 2,000 victims

00:05:10.870 --> 00:05:13.260
and secured over
100 convictions.

00:05:13.260 --> 00:05:14.870
That's in one year.

00:05:14.870 --> 00:05:19.870
Over the past 18 years, IJM has
rescued over 18,000 victims,

00:05:19.870 --> 00:05:22.390
trained 13,000
officers and officials

00:05:22.390 --> 00:05:24.730
and secured over 700
convictions, much of them

00:05:24.730 --> 00:05:26.850
in the past five years alone.

00:05:26.850 --> 00:05:28.350
However, more
significant than these

00:05:28.350 --> 00:05:31.425
numbers is growing evidence
that IJM's model is beginning

00:05:31.425 --> 00:05:34.820
to result in structural
transformation and hopefully

00:05:34.820 --> 00:05:35.830
permanent change.

00:05:35.830 --> 00:05:38.474
A Gates Foundation-funded
study, for instance,

00:05:38.474 --> 00:05:40.890
found that the number of minors
available for exploitation

00:05:40.890 --> 00:05:46.990
in metro Ceba in the Philippines
plummeted 79% over four years.

00:05:46.990 --> 00:05:49.530
As a result of the
investigation's work in 2012,

00:05:49.530 --> 00:05:52.880
Gary received the Trafficking
In Persons Report Hero Reward.

00:05:52.880 --> 00:05:55.200
IJM was also one of
11 organizations that

00:05:55.200 --> 00:05:59.600
received a combined $11 million
grant from Google.org in 2011.

00:05:59.600 --> 00:06:02.050
A significant
portion of that grant

00:06:02.050 --> 00:06:05.020
was allocated to
syndicate IJM's model

00:06:05.020 --> 00:06:06.960
to other nonprofits in India.

00:06:06.960 --> 00:06:09.820
And in the first nine
months of 2013 alone,

00:06:09.820 --> 00:06:12.660
that initiative and your
money, Google's money,

00:06:12.660 --> 00:06:16.520
resulted in 830 victim rescues.

00:06:16.520 --> 00:06:18.640
Earlier this month,
Oxford University Press

00:06:18.640 --> 00:06:21.070
released Gary's latest
book "The Locust Effect:

00:06:21.070 --> 00:06:23.660
Why the End of Poverty
Requires the End of Violence,"

00:06:23.660 --> 00:06:25.826
written with Victor Boutros,
who's here in the front

00:06:25.826 --> 00:06:27.480
as well, federal prosecutor.

00:06:27.480 --> 00:06:29.620
Let me just say, amongst
the many endorsements

00:06:29.620 --> 00:06:31.730
that came from Bill Clinton,
Anne Marie Slaughter,

00:06:31.730 --> 00:06:33.640
Madeleine Albright,
I think my favorite

00:06:33.640 --> 00:06:35.970
is from Madeleine Albright
that says "the book is

00:06:35.970 --> 00:06:38.000
a much-needed argument
for reducing violence

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:39.854
against the poor,
and a demonstration

00:06:39.854 --> 00:06:41.270
through firsthand
stories that are

00:06:41.270 --> 00:06:44.580
both shocking and true of
why that goal is so vital.

00:06:44.580 --> 00:06:47.700
The book is both a vehicle for
sharing voices rarely heard

00:06:47.700 --> 00:06:51.550
and a declaration of faith
that with sufficient will,

00:06:51.550 --> 00:06:54.530
there are ways to halt
the physical and financial

00:06:54.530 --> 00:06:57.020
exploitation of
the disadvantaged.

00:06:57.020 --> 00:06:59.680
By reminding us that basic
legal protections are not

00:06:59.680 --> 00:07:01.760
a privilege but a
universal right,

00:07:01.760 --> 00:07:03.420
Gary Haugen has
issued a moral call

00:07:03.420 --> 00:07:06.869
to arms that informs the
brain and touches the heart."

00:07:06.869 --> 00:07:09.160
That's my hope for us today,
that we'll keep our brains

00:07:09.160 --> 00:07:12.810
and our hearts open as we
welcome Gary to Google.

