00:08:26.450 --> 00:08:29.490
But I'd like to start this
afternoon with a story much,

00:08:29.490 --> 00:08:32.440
much closer to home-- actually
just a few hours from here

00:08:32.440 --> 00:08:37.330
across the California border in
Oregon, in a rural county where

00:08:37.330 --> 00:08:39.500
there was a woman,
not too long ago,

00:08:39.500 --> 00:08:41.750
who was home alone at night.

00:08:41.750 --> 00:08:43.480
It's dark out.

00:08:43.480 --> 00:08:46.480
And she starts to
hear an intruder begin

00:08:46.480 --> 00:08:49.530
to break open her side door.

00:08:49.530 --> 00:08:53.310
And she looks over,
and sees this man

00:08:53.310 --> 00:08:55.870
breaking his way into her house.

00:08:55.870 --> 00:08:57.470
It's terrifying,
especially for her,

00:08:57.470 --> 00:09:00.780
because two weeks before,
this same man in her community

00:09:00.780 --> 00:09:03.570
had put her in the hospital
through an assault.

00:09:03.570 --> 00:09:07.620
And now he is clawing
his way into her house.

00:09:07.620 --> 00:09:09.850
So she does what any
sort of terrified person

00:09:09.850 --> 00:09:11.560
would do in their
house in America.

00:09:11.560 --> 00:09:15.100
She picks up the phone,
and she calls 911.

00:09:15.100 --> 00:09:20.130
And what proceeds is a pretty
horrific 10 minute conversation

00:09:20.130 --> 00:09:23.080
with this 911 operator
who proceeds to explain

00:09:23.080 --> 00:09:27.340
that due to budget cuts
in her rural county,

00:09:27.340 --> 00:09:31.730
law enforcement is only
operating on the weekdays.

00:09:31.730 --> 00:09:33.750
And this is a weekend.

00:09:33.750 --> 00:09:35.420
And so she's simply
explaining to her

00:09:35.420 --> 00:09:39.210
that you don't have law
enforcement in your area.

00:09:39.210 --> 00:09:40.998
Listen to this
for just a moment.

00:09:40.998 --> 00:09:41.664
[AUDIO PLAYBACK]

00:09:41.664 --> 00:09:45.410
-I don't have anybody
to send out there.

00:09:45.410 --> 00:09:49.094
Uh, you know, obviously if
he comes inside the residence

00:09:49.094 --> 00:09:51.930
and assaults you, can
you ask him to go away?

00:09:51.930 --> 00:09:54.034
Or do you know if he's
intoxicated or anything?

00:09:54.034 --> 00:09:55.034
-I've already asked him.

00:09:55.034 --> 00:09:56.707
I've already told him
I was calling you.

00:09:56.707 --> 00:09:59.814
He's broken in before, busted
down my door, assaulted me.

00:09:59.814 --> 00:10:00.770
-Uh huh.

00:10:00.770 --> 00:10:04.372
Is there any way you can
safely leave the residence?

00:10:04.372 --> 00:10:06.010
-No, I can't.

00:10:06.010 --> 00:10:08.264
Because he's blocking
pretty much my only way out.

00:10:08.264 --> 00:10:10.555
-Well, the only thing I can
do is give you some advice.

00:10:10.555 --> 00:10:13.455
And call the sheriff's
office tomorrow,

00:10:13.455 --> 00:10:19.030
Obviously, if he comes in and
unfortunately, has a weapon

00:10:19.030 --> 00:10:21.435
or is trying to cause
you physical harm,

00:10:21.435 --> 00:10:22.552
that's a different story.

00:10:22.552 --> 00:10:24.343
The sheriff's office
doesn't work up there.

00:10:24.343 --> 00:10:26.315
I don't have anybody to send.

00:10:26.315 --> 00:10:28.780
[END AUDIO PLAYBACK]

00:10:28.780 --> 00:10:31.360
GARY HAUGEN: The Sheriff's
office doesn't work up there.

00:10:31.360 --> 00:10:34.690
I don't have anybody to send.

00:10:34.690 --> 00:10:39.140
Of course, what happens is
that man tears into that place,

00:10:39.140 --> 00:10:43.610
assaults her, chokes
her, brutally rapes her.

00:10:43.610 --> 00:10:46.840
This is what happens
if there's no law

00:10:46.840 --> 00:10:52.300
enforcement in your area, if
there's no one to send for you.

00:10:52.300 --> 00:10:54.090
And yet, this book
that we've written,

00:10:54.090 --> 00:10:56.180
"The Locust Effect,"
what this is about

00:10:56.180 --> 00:10:58.880
is the story that there are
about four billion people

00:10:58.880 --> 00:11:02.900
in our world who have no
access to law enforcement.

00:11:02.900 --> 00:11:04.710
Especially for those
who are poorest,

00:11:04.710 --> 00:11:08.790
a study was done by the UN that
says quote-- listen to this--

00:11:08.790 --> 00:11:14.385
"most poor people live outside
the protection of law."

00:11:14.385 --> 00:11:16.010
Now that's a phrase
that we can sort of

00:11:16.010 --> 00:11:18.066
read and just let wash over us.

00:11:18.066 --> 00:11:20.440
But I think there's perhaps
nothing quite like this phone

00:11:20.440 --> 00:11:22.590
call that allows us
for just a moment

00:11:22.590 --> 00:11:25.730
to step into the shoes
of the common poor person

00:11:25.730 --> 00:11:28.340
in the developing world
who has no access to law

00:11:28.340 --> 00:11:32.919
enforcement and the terror that
that represents in their lives.

00:11:32.919 --> 00:11:33.960
So that's the big number.

00:11:33.960 --> 00:11:36.520
Four billion people
do not have access

00:11:36.520 --> 00:11:38.595
to law enforcement
that will actually

00:11:38.595 --> 00:11:39.720
protect them from violence.

00:11:39.720 --> 00:11:42.940
But what does that actually look
like in the developing world?

00:11:42.940 --> 00:11:44.910
Well, it looks like
this in Bolivia,

00:11:44.910 --> 00:11:47.340
where if you were
to sexually assault

00:11:47.340 --> 00:11:49.760
a child in Bolivia,
statistically,

00:11:49.760 --> 00:11:52.780
you would actually be at greater
risk of slipping in the shower

00:11:52.780 --> 00:11:54.540
and dying than you
would have ever

00:11:54.540 --> 00:11:57.770
being sent to jail
for that crime.

00:11:57.770 --> 00:12:00.030
Imagine a state of
such impunity-- yes,

00:12:00.030 --> 00:12:02.260
it's completely against the law.

00:12:02.260 --> 00:12:05.170
But the problem for the poor is
not that they don't get laws,

00:12:05.170 --> 00:12:07.980
it's they don't get
law enforcement.

00:12:07.980 --> 00:12:12.220
This means, in India and
other places in South Asia,

00:12:12.220 --> 00:12:17.730
if you enslave someone,
literally enslave someone,

00:12:17.730 --> 00:12:20.230
you're at greater risk of being
struck by lightning than you

00:12:20.230 --> 00:12:25.880
are of ever being sent to
jail for the crime of slavery.

00:12:25.880 --> 00:12:30.400
This is a profound
and massive phenomenon

00:12:30.400 --> 00:12:33.270
across the developing world
that receives very, very

00:12:33.270 --> 00:12:36.520
little mention at all,
which is the utter breakdown

00:12:36.520 --> 00:12:38.950
of basic criminal justice
systems in the developing

00:12:38.950 --> 00:12:39.450
world.

00:12:39.450 --> 00:12:43.500
And what it has done, then,
is unleash this epidemic

00:12:43.500 --> 00:12:45.670
of violence against the poor.

00:12:45.670 --> 00:12:47.420
And in "The Locust
Effect," this is really

00:12:47.420 --> 00:12:49.169
what we're trying to
bring to the surface.

00:12:49.169 --> 00:12:51.800
Because if I say the
word global poverty

00:12:51.800 --> 00:12:54.020
and if you try to bring
sort of images to mind,

00:12:54.020 --> 00:12:55.030
what comes to mind?

00:12:55.030 --> 00:12:56.620
I mean immediately
you start to think,

00:12:56.620 --> 00:12:58.410
don't you, about dirty shacks.

00:12:58.410 --> 00:13:00.290
You think about the dirty water.

00:13:00.290 --> 00:13:01.370
You think of sickness.

00:13:01.370 --> 00:13:04.760
You think of kids who
can't go to school.

00:13:04.760 --> 00:13:08.260
You think of lack of capital,
the need for microfinance,

00:13:08.260 --> 00:13:09.870
all those sorts of needs.

00:13:09.870 --> 00:13:12.500
One of the things that does not
commonly come to the surface

00:13:12.500 --> 00:13:15.140
for us is the way
that to be poor

00:13:15.140 --> 00:13:18.970
is to be chronically
vulnerable to violence.

00:13:18.970 --> 00:13:20.560
But the problem is
all that violence

00:13:20.560 --> 00:13:22.700
stays below the surface.

00:13:22.700 --> 00:13:24.800
Many of us have traveled
to the developing world.

00:13:24.800 --> 00:13:27.630
And we've seen the dirty shacks,
the dirty water, the hunger,

00:13:27.630 --> 00:13:29.400
the people who are sick.

00:13:29.400 --> 00:13:32.180
But very few of us will ever
just visually see the violence.

00:13:32.180 --> 00:13:35.610
And so it takes something
for us to be traveling

00:13:35.610 --> 00:13:38.110
into that subterranean
world to see

00:13:38.110 --> 00:13:39.360
what that violence looks like.

00:13:39.360 --> 00:13:41.330
And this is what we try
to do in the opening

00:13:41.330 --> 00:13:44.060
chapters of "The Locust
Effect" is take you

00:13:44.060 --> 00:13:46.140
with a common poor person
in the developing world

00:13:46.140 --> 00:13:47.570
to see what this
violence is like.

00:13:47.570 --> 00:13:50.820
And we begin with
the first category

00:13:50.820 --> 00:13:53.781
of most pervasive violence
among the poor in the developing

00:13:53.781 --> 00:13:54.280
world.

00:13:54.280 --> 00:13:56.960
And that's basically
gender violence.

00:13:56.960 --> 00:13:59.720
That's sexual violence
and domestic abuse

00:13:59.720 --> 00:14:01.020
of women and girls.

00:14:01.020 --> 00:14:03.520
It is, in the collapse
of law enforcement,

00:14:03.520 --> 00:14:05.990
open season on women and girls.

00:14:05.990 --> 00:14:08.160
In fact, gender
violence accounts

00:14:08.160 --> 00:14:12.130
for more death and disability
for women and girls

00:14:12.130 --> 00:14:15.630
between the age of 15 and
44 than malaria, cancer, car

00:14:15.630 --> 00:14:19.570
accidents and war combined.

00:14:19.570 --> 00:14:23.784
This is why we're calling this
epidemic "every day violence,"

00:14:23.784 --> 00:14:25.950
because, again, if we are
familiar with the violence

00:14:25.950 --> 00:14:27.366
against the poor,
most of the time

00:14:27.366 --> 00:14:30.670
we're thinking about the sort of
catastrophic spasms of violence

00:14:30.670 --> 00:14:32.250
that are in the headlines.

00:14:32.250 --> 00:14:34.920
Like the wars, the
conflicts, and for sure,

00:14:34.920 --> 00:14:37.190
those do decimate
people's lives.

00:14:37.190 --> 00:14:39.700
And I know something about
that myself, of course,

00:14:39.700 --> 00:14:42.650
having been the director of
the genocide investigation

00:14:42.650 --> 00:14:45.130
in Rwanda where,
as Paul mentioned,

00:14:45.130 --> 00:14:48.910
I just was given this list by
UN military intelligence of 100

00:14:48.910 --> 00:14:51.490
different mass graves
and massacre sites.

00:14:51.490 --> 00:14:54.260
And we just tediously sorted
through these thousands

00:14:54.260 --> 00:14:56.690
and thousands of
people who'd been

00:14:56.690 --> 00:14:59.860
butchered by their neighbors.

00:14:59.860 --> 00:15:01.700
And when you're doing
that work, especially

00:15:01.700 --> 00:15:03.824
as an investigator, what
you're really trying to do

00:15:03.824 --> 00:15:06.330
is recreate visually
how did this happen

00:15:06.330 --> 00:15:08.320
from the forensic
evidence that's there.

00:15:08.320 --> 00:15:10.900
And what is it like for
that family pressed up

00:15:10.900 --> 00:15:14.120
against the wall of that
stadium or that school

00:15:14.120 --> 00:15:17.010
or that cathedral, as they
see those machetes coming

00:15:17.010 --> 00:15:18.800
towards them?

00:15:18.800 --> 00:15:21.530
And the thing that
was so manifest to me

00:15:21.530 --> 00:15:23.980
is that, yes, all these
Rwandans were overwhelmingly

00:15:23.980 --> 00:15:25.030
very, very poor.

00:15:25.030 --> 00:15:29.520
The average Rwandan is
living off about $0.65 a day.

00:15:29.520 --> 00:15:32.856
But in that moment of
terror, when the machetes

00:15:32.856 --> 00:15:34.480
are coming towards
you and your family,

00:15:34.480 --> 00:15:37.200
you're actually not
crying out for some food.

00:15:37.200 --> 00:15:38.917
You're not crying
out for a doctor.

00:15:38.917 --> 00:15:40.500
You're not crying
out for a microloan.

00:15:40.500 --> 00:15:44.120
You're not crying out for
a teacher in education.

00:15:44.120 --> 00:15:45.960
You're crying out for
someone to restrain

00:15:45.960 --> 00:15:48.230
the hand of that machete.

00:15:48.230 --> 00:15:52.030
And this is the thing that
makes violence different.

00:15:52.030 --> 00:15:55.710
It is a profound
affliction of the poor,

00:15:55.710 --> 00:15:58.410
but it's different than the
other problems that we engage.

00:15:58.410 --> 00:16:01.070
And this first category
of massive abuse

00:16:01.070 --> 00:16:02.280
is gender violence.

00:16:02.280 --> 00:16:05.190
But like so many things,
it stays below the surface.

00:16:05.190 --> 00:16:07.280
At the beginning
of the book, I just

00:16:07.280 --> 00:16:09.770
invite readers to come with
me to meet Lucilla who's

00:16:09.770 --> 00:16:13.490
this woman that I met in a small
town in the Andean mountains

00:16:13.490 --> 00:16:14.492
in Peru.

00:16:14.492 --> 00:16:16.700
Very common woman, lives in
a town that you would not

00:16:16.700 --> 00:16:20.340
necessarily notice or
pay any attention to,

00:16:20.340 --> 00:16:24.370
except for the fact it has
a rate of sexual assault

00:16:24.370 --> 00:16:27.080
that is worse than the sexual
assault rates that were coming

00:16:27.080 --> 00:16:30.520
out of the worst war
zones of the Congo.

00:16:30.520 --> 00:16:32.760
And if you follow through
the story of Lucilla

00:16:32.760 --> 00:16:35.600
as she has to endure
the rape and murder

00:16:35.600 --> 00:16:38.010
of her eight-year-old
daughter, who's just dumped out

00:16:38.010 --> 00:16:40.310
on the street one night.

00:16:40.310 --> 00:16:42.940
And to follow Lucilla in
what it is like for her

00:16:42.940 --> 00:16:46.920
to try to get justice in a
totally broken criminal justice

00:16:46.920 --> 00:16:49.260
system.

00:16:49.260 --> 00:16:52.830
Gender violence is
this massive epidemic

00:16:52.830 --> 00:16:55.570
against women and girls who
are poorest and most vulnerable

00:16:55.570 --> 00:16:56.340
in the world.

00:16:56.340 --> 00:16:59.760
The second massive category
of violence against the poor

00:16:59.760 --> 00:17:01.640
is a kind of violence
that actually

00:17:01.640 --> 00:17:05.150
keeps people in poverty by
force, and that's slavery.

00:17:05.150 --> 00:17:08.890
You may already know that there
are about 30 million people

00:17:08.890 --> 00:17:12.010
held in slavery in
the world today.

00:17:12.010 --> 00:17:14.950
These are not people held
in slave-like conditions

00:17:14.950 --> 00:17:18.050
or metaphorical slavery--
in actual slavery.

00:17:18.050 --> 00:17:20.970
At IJM, we've met
thousands of them.

00:17:20.970 --> 00:17:22.589
And thanks to
Google's work with us

00:17:22.589 --> 00:17:25.050
have also been able to
bring rescue to thousands.

00:17:25.050 --> 00:17:27.630
But there remain
actually more people

00:17:27.630 --> 00:17:32.780
in slavery today than in any
other time in human history.

00:17:32.780 --> 00:17:34.540
Mind boggling, right?

00:17:34.540 --> 00:17:37.120
It's true that a smaller
proportion of human beings

00:17:37.120 --> 00:17:37.890
are in slavery.

00:17:37.890 --> 00:17:38.920
That's true.

00:17:38.920 --> 00:17:40.740
A smaller proportion
of the economy

00:17:40.740 --> 00:17:42.020
is produced by slave labor.

00:17:42.020 --> 00:17:42.520
That's true.

00:17:42.520 --> 00:17:44.930
But there's just so
many more human beings

00:17:44.930 --> 00:17:47.070
that the absolute number
of people in slavery

00:17:47.070 --> 00:17:50.380
is greater now than any
other time in history.

00:17:50.380 --> 00:17:52.720
One of the ways we try to
bring readers into this again

00:17:52.720 --> 00:17:55.390
subterranean reality
is to take people

00:17:55.390 --> 00:17:59.180
to Bangalore, which is sort of
the shining high-tech capital

00:17:59.180 --> 00:18:03.860
in India, really sort of the
icon of the booming economies

00:18:03.860 --> 00:18:05.160
of India.

00:18:05.160 --> 00:18:08.050
But an Indian lawyer takes me
on a drive just a few minutes

00:18:08.050 --> 00:18:10.390
outside the beltway
of Bangalore and shows

00:18:10.390 --> 00:18:12.130
me a brick factory
where scores of people

00:18:12.130 --> 00:18:15.160
are held literally as slaves
working seven days a week,

00:18:15.160 --> 00:18:18.700
12 to 14 hours a day,
making and carrying bricks.

00:18:18.700 --> 00:18:20.450
And anybody's who's
ever tried to run away

00:18:20.450 --> 00:18:22.190
from the facility
is chased down,

00:18:22.190 --> 00:18:24.170
dragged back and beaten
in front of the others.

00:18:24.170 --> 00:18:28.157
In fact, when this one
couple was able to escape,

00:18:28.157 --> 00:18:30.740
the owner of the brick factory
was able to go to their village

00:18:30.740 --> 00:18:33.910
and actually kidnap and
hold some family members

00:18:33.910 --> 00:18:36.780
and neighbors as
hostages, and just

00:18:36.780 --> 00:18:39.390
publicly proclaim until you
bring me back my slaves,

00:18:39.390 --> 00:18:44.470
I'm going to continue to detain
and torture their neighbors.

00:18:44.470 --> 00:18:47.437
In other words, he was
very happy to let everyone

00:18:47.437 --> 00:18:49.520
know that he was exercising
this kind of violence,

00:18:49.520 --> 00:18:52.600
because he had zero
fear that he would ever

00:18:52.600 --> 00:18:55.350
be brought to account
under the law.

00:18:55.350 --> 00:18:58.300
So I got a chance to sit
with Mariamam for instance,

00:18:58.300 --> 00:19:01.010
as she explained what
it was like to live

00:19:01.010 --> 00:19:04.300
as a slave with her
family and about two dozen

00:19:04.300 --> 00:19:07.200
other over of her
neighbors as literal slaves

00:19:07.200 --> 00:19:10.410
in the 21st century.

00:19:10.410 --> 00:19:13.440
So the book takes us again
to that subterranean world

00:19:13.440 --> 00:19:16.930
that we would otherwise
have no idea about.

00:19:16.930 --> 00:19:18.800
The third sort of
catastrophic form

00:19:18.800 --> 00:19:21.290
of violence against the
poor, surprisingly perhaps,

00:19:21.290 --> 00:19:24.040
is police abuse.

00:19:24.040 --> 00:19:26.740
It turns out that
the World Bank did

00:19:26.740 --> 00:19:28.710
this study called
"Voices of the Poor"

00:19:28.710 --> 00:19:31.340
which gave to the tens of
thousands of poor people

00:19:31.340 --> 00:19:34.400
just the chance to say what is
it about your poverty that's

00:19:34.400 --> 00:19:36.280
most painful to you.

00:19:36.280 --> 00:19:38.140
And the study was
very rigorous, and one

00:19:38.140 --> 00:19:44.100
of things it was
saying that police

00:19:44.100 --> 00:19:46.170
and courts in the
developing world

00:19:46.170 --> 00:19:50.910
actually make poor people
poorer and less secure.

00:19:50.910 --> 00:19:51.845
What?

00:19:51.845 --> 00:19:53.220
I mean that's like
a finding that

00:19:53.220 --> 00:19:55.130
says the hospitals in
the developing world

00:19:55.130 --> 00:19:56.940
are making everybody sicker.

00:19:56.940 --> 00:19:58.820
Or the schools are
actually the places

00:19:58.820 --> 00:20:01.760
where everyone's
prohibited from reading.

00:20:01.760 --> 00:20:03.290
This is what public
justice systems

00:20:03.290 --> 00:20:05.180
have become in the
developing world--

00:20:05.180 --> 00:20:06.490
places actually of harm.

00:20:06.490 --> 00:20:08.960
If you're poor, you run away
from the police to be safe.

00:20:08.960 --> 00:20:12.130
You don't run to the
police to be safe.

00:20:12.130 --> 00:20:13.550
One of the
manifestations of this

00:20:13.550 --> 00:20:17.620
is the reality of pretrial
detention, where the police are

00:20:17.620 --> 00:20:20.400
able to throw people
into jails and hold them

00:20:20.400 --> 00:20:22.500
without any charge or trial.

00:20:22.500 --> 00:20:25.470
In any given year, there's
about 10 million people,

00:20:25.470 --> 00:20:28.460
overwhelmingly the poorest, who
are held in pretrial detention.

00:20:28.460 --> 00:20:30.307
What you don't see in
that statistic though,

00:20:30.307 --> 00:20:31.890
that of the tens of
millions of people

00:20:31.890 --> 00:20:34.440
who are attached to
those families, when

00:20:34.440 --> 00:20:36.740
the breadwinner is
taken into prison,

00:20:36.740 --> 00:20:39.660
the way that devastates
the capacity of that family

00:20:39.660 --> 00:20:41.170
to move forward.

00:20:41.170 --> 00:20:45.910
So police abuse is the
third and just horrific form

00:20:45.910 --> 00:20:47.780
of violence
confronting the poor.

00:20:47.780 --> 00:20:52.400
The fourth, interestingly,
is violent land theft.

00:20:52.400 --> 00:20:55.200
Just a way that the poor
will have their land stolen

00:20:55.200 --> 00:20:57.690
from them by people
of power and violence.

00:20:57.690 --> 00:21:01.640
In any given year,
about 5 million people

00:21:01.640 --> 00:21:05.505
will get themselves violently
ejected off of their land.

00:21:05.505 --> 00:21:06.880
And if you were
to look at, well,

00:21:06.880 --> 00:21:08.420
who's most vulnerable
to this, it

00:21:08.420 --> 00:21:11.810
turns out that widows are,
especially widows in Africa.

00:21:11.810 --> 00:21:13.560
As the AIDS epidemic
has devastated

00:21:13.560 --> 00:21:17.440
much of the male population, it
leaves these families, right?

00:21:17.440 --> 00:21:20.160
And what happens is that
stronger families will come

00:21:20.160 --> 00:21:23.270
and they'll just throw a
widow like Susan and her kids

00:21:23.270 --> 00:21:25.150
off their land.

00:21:25.150 --> 00:21:28.590
One of the things that's amazing
that I had no understanding of

00:21:28.590 --> 00:21:33.040
was the idea that widows like
Susan in the developing world

00:21:33.040 --> 00:21:36.279
support a half a
billion orphans.

00:21:36.279 --> 00:21:38.070
So you imagine a poor
person who their sort

00:21:38.070 --> 00:21:40.070
of one asset for
moving out of poverty

00:21:40.070 --> 00:21:42.210
is their little plot of
land, which gives them

00:21:42.210 --> 00:21:45.540
a little shelter and then also
the little garden where they're

00:21:45.540 --> 00:21:46.540
able to raise some food.

00:21:46.540 --> 00:21:49.830
But if you steal that
land away, you've

00:21:49.830 --> 00:21:55.220
taken a very most basic means
for progress away from them.

00:21:55.220 --> 00:21:57.640
And you've left
them in destitution.

00:21:57.640 --> 00:22:00.800
So that's the fourth
largest pervasive form

00:22:00.800 --> 00:22:04.365
of violence against the
poor is violent land theft.

00:22:08.520 --> 00:22:11.450
The things that we want to
bring forth from the book

00:22:11.450 --> 00:22:14.410
is not only this sort of
subterranean world of violence

00:22:14.410 --> 00:22:18.320
that we might not be aware of--
and why aren't we aware of it?

00:22:18.320 --> 00:22:20.410
It's hard to visualize--
but secondly, there's

00:22:20.410 --> 00:22:23.310
human beings actively hiding it.

00:22:23.310 --> 00:22:26.340
Dirty water does not
actively hide itself.

00:22:26.340 --> 00:22:29.620
Nor do shacks nor generally
do diseases, but human beings

00:22:29.620 --> 00:22:32.530
when they commit violence,
they work hard to hide it.

00:22:32.530 --> 00:22:34.620
And likewise, the
survivors and victims

00:22:34.620 --> 00:22:37.650
of abuse also because of
fear and shame many times

00:22:37.650 --> 00:22:39.260
are also hiding it as well.

00:22:39.260 --> 00:22:41.850
So the book is trying to bring
this back up to the surface.

00:22:41.850 --> 00:22:44.650
But not only that,
but help people

00:22:44.650 --> 00:22:47.750
begin to think about what
are the implications of this

00:22:47.750 --> 00:22:49.890
for our dreams for
the poor, that is,

00:22:49.890 --> 00:22:52.592
that they would be able
to get out of poverty.

00:22:52.592 --> 00:22:54.800
And this is why we're calling
it "The Locust Effect,"

00:22:54.800 --> 00:22:57.120
because one of the pictures
we want people to have

00:22:57.120 --> 00:23:01.829
is just the way that
over the millennia,

00:23:01.829 --> 00:23:03.620
these poor farm
communities, who are trying

00:23:03.620 --> 00:23:06.530
to scrape their way out of
poverty by all this farm work,

00:23:06.530 --> 00:23:10.090
in a single day would
see the locusts descend

00:23:10.090 --> 00:23:13.020
and just destroy
all of those years

00:23:13.020 --> 00:23:14.500
of hard work in a single day.

00:23:14.500 --> 00:23:16.220
And this is the way
predatory violence

00:23:16.220 --> 00:23:17.920
works in the life of the poor.

00:23:17.920 --> 00:23:22.590
In a moment, they descend
and destroy that work.

00:23:22.590 --> 00:23:25.140
But not only did it destroy
the fruit of the farm work,

00:23:25.140 --> 00:23:27.630
but what's interesting
about the locust is

00:23:27.630 --> 00:23:31.440
that farm work doesn't
stop the locust.

00:23:31.440 --> 00:23:33.330
So not only does
violence destroy

00:23:33.330 --> 00:23:35.790
the fruit of the
efforts of the poor

00:23:35.790 --> 00:23:38.970
and the efforts of those
who attempt to help them,

00:23:38.970 --> 00:23:42.170
but also the traditional things
that we do to assist the poor,

00:23:42.170 --> 00:23:44.310
they don't stop the violence.

00:23:44.310 --> 00:23:45.940
So that suggests
that we need to start

00:23:45.940 --> 00:23:48.580
talking about
poverty differently

00:23:48.580 --> 00:23:51.110
and start doing things
differently about poverty

00:23:51.110 --> 00:23:52.750
as well.

00:23:52.750 --> 00:23:54.820
So then that raises
the question that we

00:23:54.820 --> 00:23:57.680
try to address a bit in
the book is my goodness,

00:23:57.680 --> 00:24:01.580
why are criminal justice
systems so completely useless,

00:24:01.580 --> 00:24:04.640
backwards, brutal and broken
in the developing world?

00:24:04.640 --> 00:24:07.310
And there is four pretty
interesting surprises

00:24:07.310 --> 00:24:08.310
that explain this.

00:24:08.310 --> 00:24:11.440
One of them, which if you
traveled in the developing

00:24:11.440 --> 00:24:15.267
world you probably noticed,
but it didn't really

00:24:15.267 --> 00:24:17.350
come to your mind what it
was that you are seeing.

00:24:17.350 --> 00:24:20.570
And that is, you probably went
to a restaurant and a hotel,

00:24:20.570 --> 00:24:22.279
and you exchanged
some money, and you

00:24:22.279 --> 00:24:24.570
went to some other places,
novels and almost everywhere

00:24:24.570 --> 00:24:26.810
that you and I would go
in the developing world,

00:24:26.810 --> 00:24:31.020
someone will be there
with a gun guarding you.

00:24:31.020 --> 00:24:34.230
Because with the collapse
of public justice systems

00:24:34.230 --> 00:24:37.780
in the developing world,
what's come into its place?

00:24:37.780 --> 00:24:40.650
Well, people with wealth
and money and businesses

00:24:40.650 --> 00:24:42.770
have set up a completely
parallel system

00:24:42.770 --> 00:24:45.600
of private security.

00:24:45.600 --> 00:24:48.050
So now, in fact, in a
country like Guatemala,

00:24:48.050 --> 00:24:50.880
private security forces
are seven times larger

00:24:50.880 --> 00:24:54.380
than the public police force.

00:24:54.380 --> 00:24:58.070
In Africa, the largest
employer on the continent

00:24:58.070 --> 00:25:00.490
is private security.

00:25:00.490 --> 00:25:03.870
In a way that almost we have
not remarked upon at all,

00:25:03.870 --> 00:25:06.420
a massive social
transformation has taken place

00:25:06.420 --> 00:25:09.640
in the developing world, where
security, instead of it being

00:25:09.640 --> 00:25:12.670
a public good that's
provided to everybody

00:25:12.670 --> 00:25:16.140
through public institutions of
policing and criminal justice

00:25:16.140 --> 00:25:18.520
system has been privatized.

00:25:18.520 --> 00:25:21.420
So now there's two kinds of
people in the developing world.

00:25:21.420 --> 00:25:24.670
Those who can pay for their own
security and those who cannot

00:25:24.670 --> 00:25:27.880
afford to pay for security,
cannot pay to be safe,

00:25:27.880 --> 00:25:29.410
and so they're not.

00:25:29.410 --> 00:25:35.920
So we now have to picture 2 and
1/2 billion people who live off

00:25:35.920 --> 00:25:39.370
less than $2 a day, who
cannot purchase into their own

00:25:39.370 --> 00:25:42.750
security and are living
in this lawless chaos.

00:25:42.750 --> 00:25:47.060
What is the impact for them on
trying to get out of poverty?

00:25:47.060 --> 00:25:48.770
There's several
other explanations

00:25:48.770 --> 00:25:51.130
in the book that are
pretty surprising about how

00:25:51.130 --> 00:25:54.960
it is that criminal justice
systems and law enforcement has

00:25:54.960 --> 00:25:57.199
become so broken in
the developing world.

00:25:57.199 --> 00:25:58.740
But then what we
try to do is finally

00:25:58.740 --> 00:26:01.330
sort of pivot towards
some hope, because I

00:26:01.330 --> 00:26:04.140
realize I've pretty much
decimated your Wednesday

00:26:04.140 --> 00:26:07.910
right here that was going
along very well just fine.

00:26:07.910 --> 00:26:10.220
And then we hear about
all this massive violence

00:26:10.220 --> 00:26:11.110
and human suffering.

00:26:11.110 --> 00:26:13.090
It's like, thank
you very much, Gary.

00:26:13.090 --> 00:26:16.080
I'll take a nap now.

00:26:16.080 --> 00:26:20.430
But we've been at this work
now for almost 20 years.

00:26:20.430 --> 00:26:22.730
And you think we'd be pretty
much in a fetal position

00:26:22.730 --> 00:26:25.940
somewhere, because of all the
sort of overwhelming corruption

00:26:25.940 --> 00:26:27.680
and abuse and violence.

00:26:27.680 --> 00:26:30.060
But actually I have never
been and we've never

00:26:30.060 --> 00:26:33.170
been more hopeful about
coming to a tipping

00:26:33.170 --> 00:26:36.540
point of transformation
in the developing world.

00:26:36.540 --> 00:26:37.480
And why is that?

00:26:37.480 --> 00:26:38.940
Where is the hope come from?

00:26:38.940 --> 00:26:42.490
The first place that hope
comes from is history.

00:26:42.490 --> 00:26:43.990
Most of us just
have never thought

00:26:43.990 --> 00:26:47.790
for a few minutes of like,
where did our own reasonably

00:26:47.790 --> 00:26:50.480
functioning public
justice systems come from?

00:26:50.480 --> 00:26:52.500
Our public justice system,
our police and courts

00:26:52.500 --> 00:26:53.870
aren't perfect, for sure.

00:26:53.870 --> 00:26:56.060
I spent a career at the
Department of Justice

00:26:56.060 --> 00:27:00.010
going after corrupt and brutal
cops in the United States.

00:27:00.010 --> 00:27:02.830
And my co-author Victor
d does this currently

00:27:02.830 --> 00:27:04.413
and works in the
Civil Rights Division

00:27:04.413 --> 00:27:06.260
of the Department of Justice.

00:27:06.260 --> 00:27:09.320
All the sort of abuses that
happen anywhere in the world

00:27:09.320 --> 00:27:11.080
can also happen here.

00:27:11.080 --> 00:27:17.140
But we breathe, like the
invisible oxygen in the air,

00:27:17.140 --> 00:27:19.780
functioning criminal justice
systems that keep us safe.

00:27:19.780 --> 00:27:22.560
So we are outraged, are
we not, when it turns out

00:27:22.560 --> 00:27:25.620
that law enforcement can't
come to my house right now.

00:27:25.620 --> 00:27:28.290
That seems like a completely
intolerable situation.

00:27:28.290 --> 00:27:31.570
Because we have reasonably
functioning justice systems.

00:27:31.570 --> 00:27:33.960
But if you lived in
the San Francisco Bay

00:27:33.960 --> 00:27:39.170
Area 120 years ago, what
kind of law enforcement

00:27:39.170 --> 00:27:40.886
would you be experiencing?

00:27:40.886 --> 00:27:42.260
What I could tell
you for sure is

00:27:42.260 --> 00:27:45.360
that it would be either
non-existent brutal or corrupt

00:27:45.360 --> 00:27:47.040
or completely
captured by whatever

00:27:47.040 --> 00:27:49.539
local political
party was in charge.

00:27:49.539 --> 00:27:51.080
In fact, what we do
in the book is we

00:27:51.080 --> 00:27:53.660
set forth these various
examples, these scenarios,

00:27:53.660 --> 00:27:54.990
and have you try to guess.

00:27:54.990 --> 00:27:59.010
Is this one of the familiar
cities that you enjoy and walk

00:27:59.010 --> 00:28:01.780
in currently and a story of
what their public justice

00:28:01.780 --> 00:28:04.040
system looked like
140 years ago?

00:28:04.040 --> 00:28:07.240
Or is this a current city
in the developing world?

00:28:07.240 --> 00:28:11.730
And the descriptions are
indistinguishable, one

00:28:11.730 --> 00:28:12.860
from another.

00:28:12.860 --> 00:28:15.990
In other words, criminal justice
systems that work and protect

00:28:15.990 --> 00:28:17.710
people, they don't
descend from heaven

00:28:17.710 --> 00:28:19.550
as wonderfully operating.

00:28:19.550 --> 00:28:22.750
They always start out
brutal and corrupt.

00:28:22.750 --> 00:28:28.000
And a fight is engaged to make
them actually serve everybody,

00:28:28.000 --> 00:28:30.501
so that everybody's
protected from violence.

00:28:30.501 --> 00:28:33.000
And this is the history that
most of us have just forgotten.

00:28:33.000 --> 00:28:36.150
But what it reminds us is
that this is possible actually

00:28:36.150 --> 00:28:39.920
for those who are living in
the developing world as well.

00:28:39.920 --> 00:28:42.600
So that's the other way we begin
to turn to look for hope too,

00:28:42.600 --> 00:28:44.225
because there actually
are some stories

00:28:44.225 --> 00:28:46.730
and examples around
the world now

00:28:46.730 --> 00:28:48.600
where some best
practices are beginning

00:28:48.600 --> 00:28:51.970
to emerge of how the
international community can

00:28:51.970 --> 00:28:55.100
join with local
champions in the fight

00:28:55.100 --> 00:28:57.710
for trying to secure
justice for the poorest.

00:28:57.710 --> 00:28:59.590
One of the best
examples that we share

00:28:59.590 --> 00:29:01.500
in the book is the one
that Paul alluded to,

00:29:01.500 --> 00:29:04.800
which was this experiment we
did with the Gates Foundation

00:29:04.800 --> 00:29:07.030
in the second largest
city of the Philippines

00:29:07.030 --> 00:29:09.970
called Ceba which had a
terrible problem with child sex

00:29:09.970 --> 00:29:11.150
trafficking.

00:29:11.150 --> 00:29:13.390
And we were given
this grant to look at,

00:29:13.390 --> 00:29:15.680
well, let's see if
we can do two things.

00:29:15.680 --> 00:29:19.620
Number one can we stand up local
law enforcement, the police

00:29:19.620 --> 00:29:22.250
and the courts so they
actually effectively enforce

00:29:22.250 --> 00:29:24.240
the law against child
sex trafficking.

00:29:24.240 --> 00:29:25.260
Is that even possible?

00:29:25.260 --> 00:29:27.490
Because maybe it's so
hopelessly corrupt and brutal

00:29:27.490 --> 00:29:29.150
that's not even possible.

00:29:29.150 --> 00:29:31.560
And if that does happen,
will that actually

00:29:31.560 --> 00:29:34.000
reduce the amount of
violence against kids

00:29:34.000 --> 00:29:35.450
in the commercial sex trade?

00:29:35.450 --> 00:29:37.280
Or is this just
hopelessly some part

00:29:37.280 --> 00:29:39.530
of a massive problem of
poverty that will never

00:29:39.530 --> 00:29:41.790
be affected by good
law enforcement.

00:29:41.790 --> 00:29:44.530
Well, outside auditors
went in before the project

00:29:44.530 --> 00:29:46.310
began and sort of
drew a baseline

00:29:46.310 --> 00:29:48.280
of how much
victimization of children

00:29:48.280 --> 00:29:50.280
there was in the
commercial sex trade.

00:29:50.280 --> 00:29:53.000
And the goal of the project
over a four-year period of time

00:29:53.000 --> 00:29:56.360
was to try to demonstrate
a 20% reduction

00:29:56.360 --> 00:29:58.320
in the victimization
of these kids.

00:29:58.320 --> 00:30:01.370
That would have hit the ball
out of the park, home run.

00:30:01.370 --> 00:30:03.710
Gates Foundation would have
been super, super proud

00:30:03.710 --> 00:30:06.040
of this amazing winning project.

00:30:06.040 --> 00:30:09.760
But after four years of standing
up local law enforcement

00:30:09.760 --> 00:30:12.840
by deploying, as
IJM does everywhere

00:30:12.840 --> 00:30:18.450
in the world, local,
indigenous Filipino lawyers,

00:30:18.450 --> 00:30:20.740
criminal investigators
and social workers

00:30:20.740 --> 00:30:23.540
to actually turn law
enforcement around,

00:30:23.540 --> 00:30:26.840
what we saw after four short
years was their auditors

00:30:26.840 --> 00:30:31.520
found a 79% reduction in
the victimization of kids

00:30:31.520 --> 00:30:33.300
in the commercial sex trade.

00:30:33.300 --> 00:30:34.490
Why is that?

00:30:34.490 --> 00:30:36.970
Fundamentally, you
learn two things.

00:30:36.970 --> 00:30:41.210
Number one crimes against the
poor is crime of opportunity.

00:30:41.210 --> 00:30:43.151
You do it, because you
can get away with it.

00:30:43.151 --> 00:30:45.400
And it turns out that when
you can't get away with it,

00:30:45.400 --> 00:30:47.160
you don't do it anymore.

00:30:47.160 --> 00:30:49.380
It also turns out that
people who oppress the poor

00:30:49.380 --> 00:30:51.270
are not brave people.

00:30:51.270 --> 00:30:54.309
And when they start to feel
a sense of reasonable risk

00:30:54.309 --> 00:30:55.850
that they could pay
a price for that,

00:30:55.850 --> 00:30:57.884
they just leave them alone.

00:30:57.884 --> 00:30:59.800
There are a number of
stories in the book that

00:30:59.800 --> 00:31:04.640
begin to show, not only
from IJM but from other NGOs

00:31:04.640 --> 00:31:06.960
around the world, other
government organizations that

00:31:06.960 --> 00:31:11.620
are beginning to turn this
plague of violence around.

00:31:11.620 --> 00:31:14.750
Our invitation to you
is just really two-fold.

00:31:14.750 --> 00:31:18.254
One is to help us to change
the conversation about poverty.

00:31:18.254 --> 00:31:20.420
/ of you have probably been
engaged because you even

00:31:20.420 --> 00:31:21.960
came here this afternoon.

00:31:21.960 --> 00:31:24.682
You probably have some
heart for the struggle

00:31:24.682 --> 00:31:25.890
against poverty in our world.

00:31:25.890 --> 00:31:27.610
And we are at an
inflection point

00:31:27.610 --> 00:31:31.210
in history of making really
some tremendous improvements.

00:31:31.210 --> 00:31:33.960
But we're also
stalling out in terms

00:31:33.960 --> 00:31:37.320
of trying to help the
the 2 and 1/2 billion

00:31:37.320 --> 00:31:41.184
who are living off $2 a day, in
them actually breaking through.

00:31:41.184 --> 00:31:42.600
And so what we
would want to do is

00:31:42.600 --> 00:31:46.200
begin to make sure
that we don't fail

00:31:46.200 --> 00:31:48.960
to include the
problem of violence

00:31:48.960 --> 00:31:51.160
when we talk about poverty.

00:31:51.160 --> 00:31:53.700
So I would love it if you
got a hold of the book,

00:31:53.700 --> 00:31:57.010
read it, got yourself educated,
so you yourself are capable

00:31:57.010 --> 00:31:59.945
advocate of just almost
always asking the question.

00:31:59.945 --> 00:32:01.522
Yeah, but what
about the violence?

00:32:01.522 --> 00:32:03.230
And how are we dealing
with the violence?

00:32:03.230 --> 00:32:05.460
And how are we strengthening
local law enforcement

00:32:05.460 --> 00:32:07.340
to be able to address it?

00:32:07.340 --> 00:32:10.130
The second thing we
would love for you to do

00:32:10.130 --> 00:32:13.780
is not only get the book,
educate yourself, participate

00:32:13.780 --> 00:32:17.160
in the discussion,
but right now, there

00:32:17.160 --> 00:32:19.750
is a very, very important
conversation going on

00:32:19.750 --> 00:32:22.220
with the United Nations about
the Millennium Development

00:32:22.220 --> 00:32:22.927
Goals.

00:32:22.927 --> 00:32:24.260
You might have heard about this.

00:32:24.260 --> 00:32:27.260
In the year 2000,
the UN put together

00:32:27.260 --> 00:32:31.020
from the international community
a blueprint-- the blueprint--

00:32:31.020 --> 00:32:33.280
for trying to address
poverty and to try

00:32:33.280 --> 00:32:36.050
to make massive
progress over 15 years.

00:32:36.050 --> 00:32:39.210
So they came up with these
eight Millennium Goals.

00:32:39.210 --> 00:32:41.790
Well, in many
respects, those have

00:32:41.790 --> 00:32:43.970
been really helpful
and very powerful.

00:32:43.970 --> 00:32:46.830
But one of the grand
mistakes that was made

00:32:46.830 --> 00:32:50.470
was that they drew up a
blueprint to address poverty

00:32:50.470 --> 00:32:54.320
and didn't say a word about
violence, this horrific force

00:32:54.320 --> 00:32:56.460
that undercuts so
much of what's being

00:32:56.460 --> 00:32:58.610
done to try to assist the poor.

00:32:58.610 --> 00:33:00.070
An example of
that, for instance,

00:33:00.070 --> 00:33:02.870
is girls' education in the
developing world, which

00:33:02.870 --> 00:33:08.070
is this amazingly powerful way
to actually bring prosperity

00:33:08.070 --> 00:33:10.900
to a whole community, not
only for the individual girls

00:33:10.900 --> 00:33:12.700
but for that whole community.

00:33:12.700 --> 00:33:14.380
The problem is now
studies show that one

00:33:14.380 --> 00:33:15.890
of the primary
reasons girls don't

00:33:15.890 --> 00:33:19.200
go to school in the developing
world is because of violence.

00:33:19.200 --> 00:33:21.140
Violence on the way
to school, violence

00:33:21.140 --> 00:33:22.700
in school, violence
in the home that

00:33:22.700 --> 00:33:24.690
keeps them from going to school.

00:33:24.690 --> 00:33:27.780
And so we want to make
sure that as the UN now

00:33:27.780 --> 00:33:31.170
is rewriting the Millennium
Development Goals, so

00:33:31.170 --> 00:33:34.370
that in the year
2015, they'll launch

00:33:34.370 --> 00:33:36.940
this new blueprint for
addressing poverty,

00:33:36.940 --> 00:33:38.510
we just simply
want to make sure,

00:33:38.510 --> 00:33:40.420
let's not leave out violence.

00:33:40.420 --> 00:33:42.460
It's a bit like
the AIDS epidemic

00:33:42.460 --> 00:33:45.020
when it began to really
roll through the developing

00:33:45.020 --> 00:33:46.730
world in the '90s.

00:33:46.730 --> 00:33:50.100
And millions of people
were being decimated.

00:33:50.100 --> 00:33:56.145
Really you could not be serious
about addressing poverty

00:33:56.145 --> 00:33:57.974
in the developing
world if you are not

00:33:57.974 --> 00:33:59.640
willing to confront
the problem of AIDS,

00:33:59.640 --> 00:34:01.390
because whatever it
is that you are doing,

00:34:01.390 --> 00:34:03.490
AIDS is going to show
up and impact it.

00:34:03.490 --> 00:34:06.900
In the same way, we are hoping
to engage the conversation

00:34:06.900 --> 00:34:09.460
about poverty in the
developing world to say,

00:34:09.460 --> 00:34:11.670
unless you're dealing with
the problem of violence

00:34:11.670 --> 00:34:13.949
and the lawlessness
unleashed by the collapse

00:34:13.949 --> 00:34:15.699
of criminal justice
system, it's going

00:34:15.699 --> 00:34:18.989
to roll over almost everything
else you're trying to do.

00:34:18.989 --> 00:34:22.449
And so we would love
it if you would go

00:34:22.449 --> 00:34:26.199
to the
locusteffect.com/petition,

00:34:26.199 --> 00:34:28.100
and just joined
a petition there.

00:34:28.100 --> 00:34:31.500
That goes to the Secretary
General of the UN.

00:34:31.500 --> 00:34:34.020
It ought to just be
millions of common people

00:34:34.020 --> 00:34:36.662
who say, as they did with regard
to the AIDS epidemic, hey,

00:34:36.662 --> 00:34:38.120
I'm not an expert
about everything,

00:34:38.120 --> 00:34:39.415
but I care about this stuff.

00:34:39.415 --> 00:34:41.790
And it seems to make sense to
me that if we don't address

00:34:41.790 --> 00:34:44.040
violence, we're not going
to make the progress that we

00:34:44.040 --> 00:34:45.360
want in addressing poverty.

00:34:45.360 --> 00:34:46.380
Simple as that.

00:34:46.380 --> 00:34:50.080
But what I can tell you is
that this stuff matters.

00:34:50.080 --> 00:34:52.340
And it's a tremendous
way for you

00:34:52.340 --> 00:34:54.210
not only to engage
yourself, but begin

00:34:54.210 --> 00:34:57.450
to mobilize all of your
networks into the fight.

00:34:57.450 --> 00:35:00.880
So that's all I have to
share this afternoon.

00:35:00.880 --> 00:35:03.470
I'd be happy to take
questions or interaction.

00:35:03.470 --> 00:35:07.290
AUDIENCE: In your first example,
the local police station

00:35:07.290 --> 00:35:09.030
had lost funding.

00:35:09.030 --> 00:35:12.330
So my question to you would
be in these developing world,

00:35:12.330 --> 00:35:14.730
where the governments
themselves often

00:35:14.730 --> 00:35:18.239
lack funding, if you
have any ideas for

00:35:18.239 --> 00:35:19.280
had to attack that angle.

00:35:19.280 --> 00:35:20.105
GARY HAUGEN: Yeah.

00:35:20.105 --> 00:35:23.560
In many respects, we'll
look in the developing world

00:35:23.560 --> 00:35:26.292
and we'll see, especially
in low income countries,

00:35:26.292 --> 00:35:28.910
you think, wow, they really
don't have enough resources

00:35:28.910 --> 00:35:30.326
in the country to
actually provide

00:35:30.326 --> 00:35:31.470
for decent law enforcement.

00:35:31.470 --> 00:35:33.150
Except when you look
at all the dollars

00:35:33.150 --> 00:35:35.680
that are being spent
on private security.

00:35:35.680 --> 00:35:37.750
And then you realize,
oh, in the aggregate,

00:35:37.750 --> 00:35:39.730
this economy actually
has plenty of money

00:35:39.730 --> 00:35:44.010
to be able to provide for public
security, public law and order.

00:35:44.010 --> 00:35:48.380
And so what it takes
is a groundswell

00:35:48.380 --> 00:35:55.060
of social demand within
these communities--

00:35:55.060 --> 00:35:58.030
a groundswell of demand
to actually reallocate

00:35:58.030 --> 00:36:03.460
resources to the priority of
providing for law enforcement.

00:36:03.460 --> 00:36:05.450
That's why I want to
emphasize this is not

00:36:05.450 --> 00:36:09.580
a problem is going to be solved
from outsiders paratrooping

00:36:09.580 --> 00:36:12.250
in and setting up
American justice systems

00:36:12.250 --> 00:36:13.220
or something like that.

00:36:13.220 --> 00:36:17.160
This is a fight that the
community itself, the nation,

00:36:17.160 --> 00:36:19.030
must own.

00:36:19.030 --> 00:36:23.210
And part of that is to
rally the community,

00:36:23.210 --> 00:36:27.280
to begin to demand that the
public justice system is well

00:36:27.280 --> 00:36:28.542
provided for.

00:36:28.542 --> 00:36:30.750
So that's one of the things
the International Justice

00:36:30.750 --> 00:36:31.670
Mission does.

00:36:31.670 --> 00:36:34.540
And a number of
the other examples

00:36:34.540 --> 00:36:36.190
that we given in the
book is how do we

00:36:36.190 --> 00:36:39.930
come alongside local
champions in those communities

00:36:39.930 --> 00:36:42.780
and help resource them to
be able to draw attention

00:36:42.780 --> 00:36:48.210
to the problem, but
also realign resources

00:36:48.210 --> 00:36:50.040
so they're providing
for a public justice

00:36:50.040 --> 00:36:53.370
system that cares for all.

00:36:53.370 --> 00:36:57.320
One of the amazing, of
course, examples of this

00:36:57.320 --> 00:37:01.740
is the country of Georgia, which
is a former Soviet republic,

00:37:01.740 --> 00:37:07.240
which in 2003 was ranked
something like 145 out of 190

00:37:07.240 --> 00:37:09.320
countries as most corrupt.

00:37:09.320 --> 00:37:11.660
It was ranked as more corrupt
than any country that we

00:37:11.660 --> 00:37:14.370
work in, especially the police.

00:37:14.370 --> 00:37:17.830
But there was a demand
amongst the citizenry

00:37:17.830 --> 00:37:20.540
and a new election that
brought to bear leaders

00:37:20.540 --> 00:37:23.240
into power who began
to attack corruption.

00:37:23.240 --> 00:37:25.130
And they started with
police corruption.

00:37:25.130 --> 00:37:27.790
And the thing that
they found was

00:37:27.790 --> 00:37:32.220
that police officers in Georgia
would pay a $10,000 bribe

00:37:32.220 --> 00:37:34.280
in order to get a job,
for which they were

00:37:34.280 --> 00:37:37.780
paid by the government
$10 a month.

00:37:37.780 --> 00:37:39.326
Why would you do that?

00:37:39.326 --> 00:37:41.200
Because basically you've
been given a license

00:37:41.200 --> 00:37:43.450
to then extort
money from people.

00:37:43.450 --> 00:37:46.304
And then those high authorities
in the Georgian government

00:37:46.304 --> 00:37:47.220
also figured that out.

00:37:47.220 --> 00:37:48.770
Let me see, I get $10,000 bribe.

00:37:48.770 --> 00:37:50.760
We need a lot of police.

00:37:50.760 --> 00:37:53.930
Because the more police we have,
the more bribe money I get.

00:37:53.930 --> 00:37:56.590
And so they have this
bloated police force

00:37:56.590 --> 00:37:59.520
that was ill trained and
ill equipped and completely

00:37:59.520 --> 00:38:00.660
abusive.

00:38:00.660 --> 00:38:03.930
So when this new leadership came
in, the first thing they did

00:38:03.930 --> 00:38:07.630
is they fired 16,000 police
officers in a single day, sent

00:38:07.630 --> 00:38:12.030
them home and the
city was safer.

00:38:12.030 --> 00:38:14.390
Then they rebuilt the
police from the ground up.

00:38:14.390 --> 00:38:18.830
And they were able to
pay them good wages,

00:38:18.830 --> 00:38:20.460
provide them with
good equipment,

00:38:20.460 --> 00:38:22.210
and provide them with
good management that

00:38:22.210 --> 00:38:25.490
was able to secure integrity
to the police force.

00:38:25.490 --> 00:38:31.350
And the transformation for the
common person is tremendous.

00:38:31.350 --> 00:38:32.880
So the resources are there.

00:38:32.880 --> 00:38:34.820
It's just how you allocate them.

00:38:34.820 --> 00:38:35.410
Yeah.

00:38:35.410 --> 00:38:38.130
AUDIENCE: There's a sort of
a stereotype about violence

00:38:38.130 --> 00:38:40.627
against the poor,
which is maybe part

00:38:40.627 --> 00:38:42.960
of the self-defense mechanism,
like you're saying, well,

00:38:42.960 --> 00:38:44.560
after this, we'll feel
like going and taking a nap

00:38:44.560 --> 00:38:46.690
and forgetting about the
whole thing, which is, oh,

