00:40:30.790 --> 00:40:35.430
of contaminating water or
making hospitals run badly.

00:40:35.430 --> 00:40:37.160
You could make up an
instance, I guess,

00:40:37.160 --> 00:40:38.030
in which that's the case.

00:40:38.030 --> 00:40:39.821
But for the most part,
that's not the case.

00:40:39.821 --> 00:40:43.080
But there is a massive
business of economic advantage

00:40:43.080 --> 00:40:45.120
from violence against
other human beings.

00:40:45.120 --> 00:40:46.870
And if you don't have
a good system that's

00:40:46.870 --> 00:40:48.820
prepared to fight
that, that's going

00:40:48.820 --> 00:40:52.030
to roll all over
the most vulnerable.

00:40:52.030 --> 00:40:53.950
AUDIENCE: Two kind
of related questions.

00:40:53.950 --> 00:40:56.700
Or it might just be that
I'm trying to jam two in.

00:40:56.700 --> 00:41:01.700
One, you made a good case for
how violence affects the poor.

00:41:01.700 --> 00:41:04.650
I'm curious about flipping
that around and thinking

00:41:04.650 --> 00:41:07.630
about how does poverty
actually create violence.

00:41:07.630 --> 00:41:11.880
How much of this is from
people being poor and having

00:41:11.880 --> 00:41:12.860
no other opportunities?

00:41:12.860 --> 00:41:15.380
How much does that impact
the police situation

00:41:15.380 --> 00:41:19.470
where you talk about police
who are very underpaid?

00:41:19.470 --> 00:41:21.454
And getting this
into the equation,

00:41:21.454 --> 00:41:22.870
the second part
of the question is

00:41:22.870 --> 00:41:25.920
where is the most
leverage to this.

00:41:25.920 --> 00:41:28.140
There were some big
numbers thrown out

00:41:28.140 --> 00:41:31.520
around 4 billion people without
law enforcement protection,

00:41:31.520 --> 00:41:33.526
30 million in
slavery, where do we

00:41:33.526 --> 00:41:34.900
get the most
leverage to actually

00:41:34.900 --> 00:41:38.274
have the most impact
on a problem like this?

00:41:38.274 --> 00:41:39.690
GARY HAUGEN: From
our perspective,

00:41:39.690 --> 00:41:42.650
there's no question that
the biggest leverage comes

00:41:42.650 --> 00:41:45.940
from a credible criminal
deterrent in the community.

00:41:45.940 --> 00:41:52.200
Because crime proceeds
along elasticity to risk.

00:41:52.200 --> 00:41:55.940
And different kinds of
crime is sensitive to risk

00:41:55.940 --> 00:41:56.840
in different ways.

00:41:56.840 --> 00:41:59.890
So if you have social
pathology, sort of deviancy,

00:41:59.890 --> 00:42:03.330
that the pedophilia's sort
of a crime, where somebody,

00:42:03.330 --> 00:42:05.942
just out of deviancy, is
going to commit that crime.

00:42:05.942 --> 00:42:07.900
And actually, it's not
very responsive to risk.

00:42:07.900 --> 00:42:10.625
You can ratchet up the
law enforcement on that,

00:42:10.625 --> 00:42:12.500
and those people commit
those crimes anyways.

00:42:12.500 --> 00:42:14.640
And they end up going to jail.

00:42:14.640 --> 00:42:17.160
So it's not very
responsive to risk.

00:42:17.160 --> 00:42:20.972
Also true with
crime of necessity,

00:42:20.972 --> 00:42:23.180
where some one feels like,
I gotta commit this crime.

00:42:23.180 --> 00:42:25.402
And., that's what a
lot of state crime

00:42:25.402 --> 00:42:26.860
is that's committed
by governments.

00:42:26.860 --> 00:42:28.776
They think I have to
torture this guy in order

00:42:28.776 --> 00:42:29.570
to stay in power.

00:42:29.570 --> 00:42:31.680
So this is a crime
of necessarity.

00:42:31.680 --> 00:42:35.970
So that responsiveness to
risk is also not that great.

00:42:35.970 --> 00:42:38.550
I also crime of
desperation where

00:42:38.550 --> 00:42:41.510
you feel like I got
a steal the bread,

00:42:41.510 --> 00:42:44.200
I have to hijack the car
because my family's starving,

00:42:44.200 --> 00:42:45.860
and so this is necessity.

00:42:45.860 --> 00:42:49.000
That's also not very
responsive to risk.

00:42:49.000 --> 00:42:51.310
But the vast,
vast, vast majority

00:42:51.310 --> 00:42:54.780
of crime against the poor
is crime of opportunity.

00:42:54.780 --> 00:42:57.550
You do it because you
can get away with it.

00:42:57.550 --> 00:42:59.280
And what you find
there on the curve

00:42:59.280 --> 00:43:01.910
is that as soon as there
is a little increase

00:43:01.910 --> 00:43:04.760
in the risk, that falls
very, very sharply,

00:43:04.760 --> 00:43:09.010
especially things like any
kind of crime of opportunity

00:43:09.010 --> 00:43:10.950
that produces an
economic reward.

00:43:10.950 --> 00:43:12.390
That's certainly like slavery.

00:43:12.390 --> 00:43:16.254
That step drops off like 79%
in a four-year period of time

00:43:16.254 --> 00:43:17.670
when people who
were doing it just

00:43:17.670 --> 00:43:21.640
for the purposes of making money
find that the risk calculation

00:43:21.640 --> 00:43:26.100
has changed so we have seen
the greatest returns from just

00:43:26.100 --> 00:43:28.867
making sure that those
who would be drawn

00:43:28.867 --> 00:43:30.950
to that crime against the
poor feel like they have

00:43:30.950 --> 00:43:32.980
a reasonable chance
of going to jail.

00:43:32.980 --> 00:43:36.840
That means you get rid
of all the soft crime.

00:43:36.840 --> 00:43:39.120
That will leave you
with a hard crime, which

00:43:39.120 --> 00:43:41.730
is the crime of desperation,
the crime of necessity,

00:43:41.730 --> 00:43:43.380
the crime of social deviancy.

00:43:43.380 --> 00:43:45.840
And in the West,
that's what we're

00:43:45.840 --> 00:43:48.840
trying to mostly battle
in our communities.

00:43:48.840 --> 00:43:52.467
But we have a really
different struggle

00:43:52.467 --> 00:43:54.050
in the developing
world, where there's

00:43:54.050 --> 00:43:56.810
a tremendous amount of soft
crime, crime of opportunity

00:43:56.810 --> 00:43:58.290
that hasn't been
addressed at all.

00:43:58.290 --> 00:44:00.540
And we will have to eventually
get to the other stuff.

00:44:00.540 --> 00:44:03.090
But right now, the
massive numbers

00:44:03.090 --> 00:44:06.010
are coming from just
pure opportunity.

00:44:06.010 --> 00:44:06.510
Yeah.

00:44:06.510 --> 00:44:12.140
The second question was
about-- the prior question--

00:44:12.140 --> 00:44:14.350
AUDIENCE: The first was, I
think, what you mentioned,

00:44:14.350 --> 00:44:17.030
which is the crimes of
necessity or desperation,

00:44:17.030 --> 00:44:19.240
that how much does
poverty itself create

00:44:19.240 --> 00:44:22.895
the violence versus violence
exacerbating the poverty?

00:44:22.895 --> 00:44:23.770
GARY HAUGEN: A cycle.

00:44:23.770 --> 00:44:24.645
They're interrelated.

00:44:27.310 --> 00:44:29.900
But it's a mistake
to imagine that you

00:44:29.900 --> 00:44:33.350
have to wait to solve poverty
before you can drastically

00:44:33.350 --> 00:44:36.050
reduce the amount of
violence against the poor.

00:44:36.050 --> 00:44:40.130
You can addressed
violence because it's

00:44:40.130 --> 00:44:43.840
driven by the incentives of
the perpetrator, substantially.

00:44:43.840 --> 00:44:47.590
And so those risk calculations
are very, very powerful.

00:44:47.590 --> 00:44:50.500
You will need to address
the other sort of caught

00:44:50.500 --> 00:44:53.940
complicated social
causes for crime.

00:44:53.940 --> 00:44:56.180
But a massive
amount of it can be

00:44:56.180 --> 00:44:59.060
addressed by addressing the
incentives of the perpetrators

00:44:59.060 --> 00:45:01.560
unlike dirty water
or disease they

00:45:01.560 --> 00:45:03.970
don't have human will behind it.

00:45:03.970 --> 00:45:05.590
All crime does.

00:45:05.590 --> 00:45:09.420
And so you affect the
incentives of the perpetrators

00:45:09.420 --> 00:45:11.842
quite powerful and faster than
you might otherwise think.

00:45:11.842 --> 00:45:14.050
AUDIENCE: I realize you're
focusing on the developing

